### Question 2

> ![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 2: Position of the ball over time starting the instant it left the hand. The equation that governs this relationship is $y = y_0 + v_{0,y}t - \frac12 gt^2$ which is a quadradic equation in $y$ and $t$ which explains the shape of our graph. We are unable to directly compute the value of $g$ from this graph as simple linear regression requires a linear original graph.

>![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 3: Velocity of the ball over time starting the instant it left the hand. the equation that governs this relation is $v = v_{0,y} -gt$ which is a linear relationship in $v$ and t which explains the shape of our graph and allows us to use simple linear regression to find the value of $g$. The equation for this trendline is in the legend at the top of the graph

>![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 4: Position of the ball over time $= \frac{t^2}{2}$. The equation that governs this relationship is $y = y_{0,y} -g(\frac{t^2}{2})$ which is approximated to be linear in $y$ and $\frac{t^2}{2}$ which again explains why our graph is very linear and allows us to find the value of $g$. The equation for the trendline is in the legend at the top of the graph. This value of $g$ is farther from the real value since we aren't actually finding $\frac{dv}{dt}$we are approximating it with imperfect data. 
### Question 3

We measured that the acceleration due to gravity $g$ was equal to $g = (-10.9 \pm 0.1) \space m/s^2$ 

The theoretical value for $g$ is $g = -9.81 \space m/s^2$ (I chose axes in Logger pro such that $g$ would be negative)

Given that the value of $g$ that we found is within 11 error intervals from the mean our value of $g$ is in complete disagreement with the theoretical value
### Question 4

We measured that the acceleration due to gravity $g$ was equal to $g = -11.27 \pm 0.02 \space m/s^2$ 

The theoretical value for $g$ is $g = -9.81 \space m/s^2$ (I chose axes in Logger pro such that $g$ would be negative)

Given that the value of $g$ that we found is within 73 error intervals from the mean our value of $g$ is in complete and total utter disagreement with the theoretical value, although disregarding the uncertainly, it is not a terrible estimate considering the technique we used
### Question 5

I chose to place the points on the left side of the ball, this was chosen to counteract the effects of motion blur on the placement of my points, If I would have chosen the top or the bottom of the ball the measurements would have been less precise since as the ball went faster it became more of a blur. Ultimately i think either side of the ball would have worked and would have given better results compared to the top or bottom
### Question 6

 - Higher framerate and quality video which would give us more points and more accurate placement of the points
 - Increase lighting and decrease shutter speed of the camera to reduce motion blur
 - Repeat the experiment multiple times and average the results of the experiments so that the random human error is reduced in the overall average
 - Control the start and end positions better, create a rig to drop the ball at a specific time ideally synced with the start of the recording so that the slight velocity that might be imparted from a human dropping it is minimized
 - Add sensors to the ball to detect the exact time it hits the ground to get a better measurement for end time
